diff:1670111774:1670111774:=1,96d0%0a%3c (:if [ authgroup @tas || authgroup @admins || equal {$Author} '' ]:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%3c %0a%3c >>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%3c %0a%3c [[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a%3c [[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]] \\%0a%3c [[{$FullName}?action=edit|Edit this page]] \\%0a%3c Status: {GradebookArticles.{$Name}$:Status} %0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%3c %0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c [[!{$:Category}]]%0a%3c %0a%3c !Naming of Colors%0a%3c %0a%3c :Author: cheng%0a%3c %0a%3c '''Summary:''' \\%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summary]]%0a%3c %0a%3c You name what you see, you see what you name. Color exposure determines color naming; color naming affects color perception.%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summaryends]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c Color is a visual perceptual property, and we have far fewer names for colors than colors we can distinguish between. Color terminologies vary cross-linguistically and interact with speakers' color cognition.%0a%3c %0a%3c On one hand, the use of color terms might depend on communicative needs. According to the article "Color naming across languages reflects color use"(1), objects (what we talk about) are typically warm-colored, and warm colors are communicated more efficiently than cool colors cross-linguistically. Communicative needs also explain why the number of color terms varies across languages: Cultures vary in how useful color is. Industrialization, which creates objects distinguishable solely based on color, increases color usefulness. In other words, you name what you see.%0a%3c %0a%3c On the other hand, the names we give to colors affect our perception of them. According to the article "The way you see colour depends on what language you speak"(2), Greek speakers have two separate color terms to describe light and dark blue – "ghalazio" and "ble", while English speakers describe both colors as "blue". After living for long periods of time in the UK, Greek speakers start to see these two colors as more similar. In other words, you see what you name.%0a%3c %0a%3c Linguistic relativity and the color naming debate is an interesting interdisciplinary topic involving cognitive linguistics. It still welcomes new perspectives and inspires many other research topics.%0a%3c %0a%3c Now I want to deviate a little and write about my confusion during my search online: In Berlin and Kay's famous study of colors, they identified 11 basic color terms in English: black, white, gray, red, green, blue, yellow, pink, orange, purple, and brown. However, there wasn’t an English word for the color “orange” until 200 years after the citrus fruit of the same name arrived in Europe. Before then, the color was called by the two other colors that, when mixed, make orange: “yellow-red.”(3) In comparison, oranges (guess why it's called mandarin) have been cultivated by Chinese people for thousands of years, but orange as a color term doesn't even make it into the 8 or 9 basic color categories according to some researchers. For instance, on WALS's map Number of Basic Colour Categories(4), I see that Chinese has 8 basic color categories instead of 11 in other popular languages. As a native Chinese speaker, I feel that the basic colors in Chinese correspond exactly to those 11 in English. From my observation, the older generation tends to describe an orange object as "orange-yellow" and pink as "pink-red", thus violating the monolexemic criteria(5), while the younger generation tends to treat "orange" or "pink" as basic colors. Maybe Mandarin Chinese keeps forming compound words or loan words and gradually "absorbs" them into a single morpheme as people love to abbreviate things. But why is Mandarin categorized as isolating in the first place? From my perspective, ancient Chinese is isolating but modern simplified Chinese is quite agglutinative.%0a%3c %0a%3c (1) https://www.pnas.org/doi/10.1073/pnas.1619666114%0a%3c (2) https://theconversation.com/the-way-you-see-colour-depends-on-what-language-you-speak-94833%0a%3c (3) https://qz.com/1454466/your-language-influences-your-color-perception-says-a-new-study%0a%3c (4) https://wals.info/feature/133A%0a%3c (5) https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linguistic_relativity_and_the_color_naming_debate#Berlin_and_Kay%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Expansions:%0a%3c [[#expansions]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#expansionsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%3c %0a%3c (:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:elseif [ equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:andrewid} '' || equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:section} '' ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c You must enter your andrew ID and section before submitting an expansion. %0a%3c %0a%3c (:else:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Comments%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c (:if equal {$Author} {$:Author}:)%0a%3c !!Change article category%0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#changearticlecategory:)%0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c (:Section: A:)%0a%3c (:Category: Varia:)%0a%3c (:Title: Naming of Colors:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
